				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I think it's as simple as each individual holding the controller differently based on his/her comfort and what works best for them, and is sometimes situational.  I actually knew a lot of people in my childhood who on the NES would switch to either thumb+index or index+middle when rapid shooting was required (think <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oJ4lmAFB7d4" class="postlink">Takahashi Meijin</a> -- and this is certainly what Asaki is referring to, re: precision), but otherwise would use only their thumb.<br /><br />As for me, I've always just used my thumb.  The reason is that the controller feels extremely uncomfortable to hold if I'm using thumb+index or index+middle.  I prefer to hold the controller and not put it on a flat/stationary surface (which is also why I hate those &quot;arcade sticks for home&quot; and hated the NES Advantage.  I hated the NES Max for other reasons).<br /><br />Now as for NES controllers in general, specifically classic/original vs. &quot;dogbone&quot; -- I *very* much prefer the dogbone simply because it fits in my hands easier (I have dainty girl-or-elf-like hands).  The square shape of the original controller made it annoying for me even when I was a kid, and come to think of it, that's probably why the SNES controller was my all-time favourite until the release of the Sony Playstation controller (which to date is still my favourite controller -- the original PS1 / grey controllers because they're lightweight and they lack analog sticks which tend to get in the way of my thumbs for non-analog games).<br /><br />On my PC, I actually use a DualShock 3 controller (hooked up via USB).</div>

