				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Myask wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">koitsu wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I hated the NES Max for other reasons.</div>Elaborate?</div><br />The &quot;disc&quot; (instead of a D-pad) was the most awful, confusing, and ridiculous bullshit I'd ever seen.<br /><br />The red disc you slide around doesn't do jack squat unless you apply a decent amount of pressure where one of the D-pad locations (up/down/left/right) would be (or possibly only if pressing against the &quot;sides&quot;?  I could never figure this out!).  As we all know, the NES only understands 4 directional inputs: up, down, left, and right (and in combination (tepples don't get OCD about left+right being pressed at the same time, STFU)).  They're binary statuses, not analogue, i.e. either you're pressing the direction or not (there is no pressure variance).<br /><br />Then there's the black ring around all of that nonsense, which had directional arrows imprinted in it, which made me wonder if *that* was what you were supposed to press with your thumb -- or press the red disc &quot;against&quot; one of those.<br /><br />It really made no sense and completely destroyed any kind of responsiveness you had to a game because you were too busy sliding a slick red disc around, like a paraplegic rubbing a clitoris.<br /><br />I had a friend who absolutely LOVED the NES Max and he could never explain to me what it was about it that he liked (still to this day).  I figured the &quot;disc&quot; layout might cater to sports games (ex. Ice Hockey, Blades of Steel, Tecmo Bowl, etc.) where diagonal directionals (ex. up+left) were more commonly used (vs. platformers or some shooting games), but that wasn't really the case (I tried it out myself on Ice Hockey and Blades of Steel).<br /><br />I had better precision using an actual D-pad, simply because the tactile response of my thumb pressing against the &quot;tips&quot; of the D-Pad (e.g. feeling thumb pressed against Up, and against Left) provided better mental feedback.  With the NES Max, you lost all of that -- instead all you had was that stupid disc.<br /><br />The ONLY thing I liked about the NES Max was the turbo buttons.  The turbo rate was incredibly fast (it's faster than the NES Advantage with the pots maxxed out) and worked very well.  Everything else on that controller was shit.  The End(tm).</div>

